iews about death and dying. In this meditative and gently humorous book, Dawdy embarks on a transformative journey across the United States, talking to funeral directors, death-care entrepreneurs, designers, cemetery owners, death doulas, and ordinary people from all walks of life. What she discovers is that, by reinventing death, Americans are reworking their ideas about personhood, ritual, and connection across generations. She also confronts the seeming contradiction that American death is becoming at the same time more materialistic and more spiritual.Written in conjunction with a documentary film project, American Afterlives features images by cinematographer Daniel Zox that provide their own testament to our rapidly changing attitudes toward death and the afterlife.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDeathxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aDeathxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aFuneral rites and ceremonieszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Death & Dying.2bisacsh  aAlign (company).  aAmbrose Bierce.  aAncient Egypt.  aApotheosis.  aArchaeology.  aAunt.  aBone china.  aBuddhism.  aBurial.  aCalifornia.  aCarbon footprint.  aCasket.  aCemetery.  aCoffin.  aCommodification.  aConservative Judaism.  aConvenience.  aCremation.  aCrematory.  aCryonics.  aCustomer.  aDay of the Dead.  aDeath mask.  aDeath.  aDisenchantment.  aEastern philosophy.  aEgyptomania.  aEmbalming chemicals.  aEmbalming.  aEmbrace Life.  aEspresso machine.  aEuthanasia.  aFantasy coffin.  aField hospital.  aForestry.  aFoyer.  aFriendship.  aFuneral director.  aFuneral home.  aGeologist.  aGrandparent.  aGrief.  aGumball machine.  aHeadstone.  aHis Family.  aHomegoing.  aHospice.  aHospital bed.  aHumility.  aIconography.  aIn Death.  aI